<TEXT>
ernice dean lives in a small 
weatherbeaten home on this tiny sea island on land that has been 
in her family for generations but the land may not belong to her 
much longer 
ms dean like hundreds of other descendants of freed slaves in 
south carolina has found she cannot keep pace with rising property 
taxes brought on by increased property values 
i was paying 280 and now i have to pay about 400 
annually said ms dean who has been forced to let four other 
people live on her property in order to pay the tax bill 
st helena island population 6230 about 40 miles from lavish 
hilton head island is one of more than 100 sea islands stretching 
from charleston to savannah ga the islands dotted with marshes 
and lined with palmetto trees were settled by slaves freed during 
the civil war 
today warm breezes and fresh seafood make the island chain a 
magnet for visitors 
but with tourism has come development that has driven up land 
prices and taxes and that threatens the residents many of whom 
are poor and subsist on what they can grow in their gardens and 
catch in the sea 
last fall beaufort county auctioned off 87 properties up 42 
percent from the previous year for about 1 million because the 
owners were unable to pay their taxes 
the main source of income the industry of tourism pays low 
wages and is seasonal said emory campbell director of the penn 
community center which has helped the islanders with land problems 
since its founding in 1862 
it emphasizes exclusivity and results in increased property 
values you find that it is extremely out of balance income from 
tourism does not sustain the increased cost of taxes housing and 
food 
tourism is a 5 billionayear industry in south carolina 
beaufort county treasurer eldrid moody also blames the countys 
spending habits the county he said spends more money and has 
more employees than many its size 
taxes are high because we refuse to control spending moody 
said my concern with beaufort county is that we dont have to 
buy the best or build the best we need to put a measuring stick on 
the ability to pay of the masses 
beaufort county has 45000 fewer residents than neighboring 
berkeley county but a budget that is greater by 99 million in 
addition the population has grown only 42 percent annually since 
1980 while the budget has mushroomed 18 percent a year moody said 
county council chairman bill bowen defended the countys budget 
and tax structure 
those quote poor people are the ones who require the most 
services from the county through welfare services and receive the 
most for their tax dollar he said 
residents who lost their property in last years tax sale have 
until october to buy it back but many are impoverished some lost 
their land for failing to pay tax bills as low as 300 
the county council has discussed the tax dilemma but bowen 
isnt sure the council should do anything 
if someone cant afford to own property because they cannot 
pay taxes then they shouldnt own the property he said if i 
cant pay my taxes because my property has gotten so valuable then 
i sell my property for a profit and move to an area where it is 
like it used to be 
there are fewer and fewer places where its like it used to 
be campbell said 
a study conducted eight years ago by the penn center found that 
35 percent of the land in beaufort county was owned by blacks he 
doesnt have current figures but believes thats decreased 
its driving people from a situation where theyre surviving 
to an innercity situation such as publicsubsidized housing or 
even a homeless situation campbell said people usually dont 
have any sympathy there needs to be some kind of recognition of 
the indigenous use of land 
before you know it the thing that attracted tourism and 
development is gone youve ruined your lakes and streams with 
marinas and youve wiped out the native population 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

