<TEXT>
saddam husseins conquest of kuwait and 
threats against saudi arabia have sharpened the interarab 
rivalries that have long thwarted hopes of forging a regional unity 
against israel 
the failure of the arabs to move against saddam for gobbling up 
a fellow arab state has underlined their inherent inability to take 
decisive collective action but the debate over the iraqi 
presidents action still rings with appeals to panarab concerns 
including declarations by the saddam himself 
the various arab factions all condemned israels seizure of arab 
lands in 1967 and saddam declared sunday he was ready to resolve 
the persian gulf crisis if israel gave up those conquests 
it was saddams own attempt to use one of the few issues that 
all arabs agree on to stir up panarab support for his cause 
most arab nations may have objected to saddams predatory 
invasion aug 2 but they split cleanly over what to do about it 
only a few have sent small military forces to help defend saudi 
arabia the arab worlds bankroller 
king fahd of saudi arabia had no choice but to call in the 
americans to defend his throne against a brother arab because no 
one else was prepared to do it 
the arab league now with 21 members was founded in 1945 to 
unite the arab world as the colonial era ended after world war ii 
but in a region riven by centuriesold tribal feuds overlaid 
with the political and territorial confrontations spawned in the 
postwar era that unity has proved to be as elusive as a desert 
mirage 
gen saad elshazly a hero in the arab world for masterminding 
the 1973 egyptian assault across the suez canal that sent the 
israelis reeling noted in his book the arab military option 
that the arab world is a mosaic 
seen from afar it looks whole but examined closely it reveals 
itself no more than a pattern of glinting multicolored fragments 
the bleak but inexorable verdict has to be that it is impossible to 
see how arab unity can be achieved in the foreseeable future 
he stresses that three diseases ravage the arab world 
debilitating its potential strength rival ideologies uneven 
economic wealth and the conflicting ambitions of its leaders 
the arab world stretches from the indian ocean to the atlantic 
from the mediterranean to the congo its 210 million people share a 
common religion islam 
all speak arabic but traditions and custom vary so much that an 
algerian arab is virtually incomprehensible to a levantine arab 
from lebanon 
the creation of israel in 1948 in what was once palestine 
should in theory have been the catalyst for bringing the 
fledgling arabs states together but it did not and to this day 
still has not 
one reason why the combined arab armies of syria jordan iraq 
lebanon and egypt failed to crush the heavily outnumbered israelis 
in the first middle east war of 194849 was that national 
jealousies prevented the creation of a unified arab command 
that remains true now three unsuccessful wars with the jewish 
state later 
all attempts at political union by some countries such as egypt 
and syria have failed because of conflicting objectives 
no two arab regimes are the same 
the rivalries stemmed in large part from the arbitrary and often 
artificial borders drawn for many of these states by the british 
and french after world war i when they carved up the old ottoman 
empire 
with iraqs annexation of kuwait which was ruled by an emir 
there are now seven monarchies most of them absolute like saudi 
arabia 
seven states have thinly veiled military or militarybacked 
dictatorships such as iraq syria and libya the others are either 
oneparty republics or emerging democracies 
iraq and syria ruled by rival wings of the baath arab socialist 
party have been feuding for more than 10 years and have backed 
different sides in lebanons 15yearold civil war 
algeria and morocco are at odds over the mineralrich western 
sahara 
syrian president hafez assad has been scrapping with plo 
chairman yasser arafat since 1983 
syria ended an 11year rift with egypt in december syria broke 
off relations with cairo in 1978 after egyptian president anwar 
sadat signed a peace treaty with israel 
amid these frustrations many arab states have settled for 
forming subregional economic and security alliances a move that 
some analysts see as evidence of a new pragmatism in the arab world 
the gulf cooperation council was founded in 1981 while the 
iraniraq war raged and includes saudi arabia oman the united 
arab emirates qatar bahrain and what was then the independent 
emirate of kuwait 
in february 1989 egypt iraq jordan and north yemen now 
united with south yemen formed the arab cooperation council 
while libya algeria tunisia morocco and mauretania joined 
together in the arab maghreb union 
saddam husseins invasion of kuwait aug 2 and his massing of 
tens of thousands of troops on saudi arabias northern border was a 
body blow to the gulf cooperation council which despite its 
jointsecurity agreement failed to rally behind kuwait 
saddams action was also a slap in the face for egypt its arab 
cooperation council partner and a leading arab moderate which had 
tried to head off the iraqi invasion 
at an emergency arab summit in cairo on friday egypt was one of 
only 12 arab states that voted for a resolution on sending troops 
to saudi arabia 
economically there are also great imbalances in the arab world 
which have exacerbated the lack of unity 
the oilrich gulf states long reveled in their petrodollar 
wealth while millions of fellow arabs have languished in poverty 
their countries burdened by mountainous debts 
sadats successor hosni mubarak has skillfully guided egypt 
back into the arab fold after a decade of ostracism by the arabs 
and clearly hoped to become the beacon for moderate forces in this 
turbulent region 
his strategy appeared to be making headway until saddam his 
regional ambitions fueled by his selfproclaimed victory in the 
198088 war against iran went on the warpath and shifted the 
center of arab gravity from cairo to baghdad 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note ed blanche the associated press middle east 
news editor based in nicosia has covered the region since 1985 
</TEXT>
