turkish officials say they do not expect an iraqi invasion 
the 64yearold ozal has led turkeys effort to rein in iraq he 
hopes turkeys strong stand against saddam will translate into more 
western support for this country particularly in its bid to join 
the european community 
ozal was elected president in 1989 after six years as prime 
minister although the presidency is normally a ceremonial post 
with little executive power he has remained turkeys most powerful 
politician 
since iraq overran kuwait ozal has clearly run the show he has 
chaired cabinet meetings plotted strategy with military chiefs and 
conducted telephone diplomacy with world leaders 
he has received most of the credit for the tough economic 
sanctions imposed against baghdad including the closure of twin 
oil pipelines across turkey that carried more than half of iraqs 
oil exports 
in his speech announcing the deployment of us troops in saudi 
arabia bush lauded ozal as a staunch friend secretary of 
state james a baker iii traveled to ankara last week to thank ozal 
for the forthright action against iraq and assure him of natos 
support in case of an iraqi attack 
but ozal does not give the impression of a man gearing up for 
war he was in istanbul recently dancing with his wife semra at a 
policemans ball when a reporter entered ozals office at the 
cankaya presidential palace for an interview he found the 
president watching cable news network and chuckling over highlights 
of a brawl between the new york mets and philadelphia phillies 
on sunday as parliament debated the war powers request ozal 
attended a horse race in istanbul 
with tensions rising ozal went on national television last week 
in a skillful performance to explain turkeys position and calm the 
nation 
he went a long way to conveying to the turkish public that the 
world was acting and turkey needed to be part of the world said 
a western diplomat 
turkeys decision to join the economic embargo of iraq was not 
an easy one not only because the country stands to suffer more 
than 2 billion in losses as a result of the un economic 
sanctions against baghdad 
just as importantly ankara has sought friendly relations with 
iraq and other moslem and arab nations of the region while at the 
same time seeking to be part of the west 
ozal a devout moslem stresses turkey has not upset its 
delicate balance between europe and asia we wear two hats as a 
modern nation allied with the west and as a member of the islamic 
bloc he said saturday we want to continue this 
until recently turkey felt it was losing importance in the eyes 
of the west following the end of the cold war but ozal hopes the 
current spotlight on turkey will give the country renewed status 
within the west 
this crisis has highlighted turkeys importance in the middle 
east as a stable and modern country he said 
ozals election by parliament was boycotted by opposition 
parties which accused him of nepotism corruption and 
highspending during his term as premier 
now the opposition accuses him of exceeding the powers of the 
presidency and violating the constitution during a heated 
parliamentary debate sunday chief opposition leader erdal inonu 
compared ozal to a dictator 
others say strong leadership is just what is needed columnist 
ilnur cevik wrote in sundays english language turkish daily news 
as we sail though the current crisis we are better off having an 
able captain than being run aground by someone else 
