<TEXT>
ask what japan will do next to help in the iraq 
crisis and the answer is it will observe the japanese 
constitution which forbids military activity 
ask what washington wants japan to do and the answer is even 
more vague no one is saying not even whether washington has put 
specific requests to tokyo 
these issues go to the heart of japans standing in the world 
today its curious mixture of confident wealth and uncertainty of 
how to play the role of a big power what specifically can japan do 
in a heated crisis to back its global partners the united states 
and other big western democracies what can it be asked to do 
the administration of prime minister toshiki kaifu left an 
impression monday of tough choices still ahead so great that kaifu 
postponed a trip to saudi arabia and four other middle east 
countries snared in the iraqi crisis 
the nub of the issue for tokyo is that an international military 
effort is growing in the middle east which is the source of 70 
percent of japans oil and japan steers clear of foreign military 
actions from painful experience a halfcentury ago 
instead of going to the middle east and showing support for the 
countries that oppose iraqs invasion of kuwait kaufu will stay at 
home to direct the government through the minefield of deciding how 
to back the international force in the persian gulf without 
violating the constitution 
japan is determined to decide on concrete measures to 
support the gulf force makoto watanabe director of the foreign 
ministrys middle eastern affairs bureau told reporters 
asked repeatedly whether japan might send military units such as 
naval vessels he stolidly replied we will examine all possible 
measures while observing the provisions of the constitution 
kaifus government already has barred trade with iraq and kuwait 
and fully supports international economic sanctions to dislodge the 
iraqis from kuwait 
the sanctions were a genuine sacrifice for japan foreign 
ministry spokesman taizo watanabe said last week japan drew 112 
percent of its oil from iraq and kuwait in the first half of this 
year while japan has 142 days worth of oil in reserve the 
government is expected to authorize modest energyconservation 
measures tuesday in case the gulf standoff drags on 
the crisis has knocked 1512 percent off the closely watched 
nikkei index on the tokyo stock exchange the big decline seems to 
belie predictions that japans economy growing strongly at more 
than 4 percent annually has a comfortable cushion in times of 
crisis 
whatever economic sacrifices emerge the tough decision for the 
japanese government is how far it can go to support a foreign 
military effort by its allies 
japans nowar constitution is better suited to a peaceful world 
that does not exist it was imposed by usled occupation 
authorities after world war ii 
the constitution declares that the japanese people forever 
renounce war as a sovereign right and that armed forces as well 
as other war potential will never be maintained 
after the outbreak of the korean war in 1950 the constitution 
was interpreted to mean that japan could maintain armed forces for 
selfdefense 
from there japans defense budget has grown to a limit of 1 
percent of gross national product but there is fierce debate 
whenever anyone suggests projecting military force abroad the 
navy for instance could have been chosen to protect 
plutoniumcarrying ships from terrorists the lowerprofile coast 
guard was picked instead 
in 1987 both sides in the iraniraq war attacked oil tankers in 
the persian gulf the united states led a multinational task force 
to clear the path for oil vital to japan but tokyo decided it 
could not send even such a defensive military unit as a minesweeper 
to the gulf because of the constitution 
instead japan financed a navigation system to keep track of 
ships in the gulf extended new loans and a credit line to jordan 
and assumed a bigger share of the cost of basing us troops in 
japan 
its most likely that japan will use money again to back the 
gulf crisis force other countries will risk manpower and prestige 
and japan will face accusations of getting a free ride again 
</TEXT>
