<TEXT>
gardner l bridge 83 an associated press 
newsman in washington and new york for 40 years died monday 
bridge died at arlington hospital of an intestinal obstruction 
his family said 
as a reporter in the associated press new york city bureau 
bridge covered such stories as the final gang wars of the 
prohibition era the lindbergh kidnapping the ss morro castle 
disaster and the investigation of mayor jimmy walkers 
administration 
in washington bridge covered the senate and was assigned to 
every national political convention from 1944 to 1968 
while riding the thomas e dewey campaign train in 1944 bridge 
and several others were injured in a train wreck at castle rock 
wash dewey was not injured 
bridge was born nov 2 1906 in stockbridge ny and grew up 
in syracuse ny 
he began his career with the associated press in 1925 as a morse 
code operator at the same time he attended classes at columbia 
universitys graduate school of journalism 
he took a job as a reporter for the albany evening news in 1928 
and went on to cover the state legislature for the newspaper 
bridge returned to the associated press in new york in 1931 as a 
reporter and later became city editor and bureau chief 
he transferred to washington in 1942 and retired in 1971 
bridge is survived by two daughters vivian bridge of reston and 
regina steele of fairfax two grandchildren and one great grandson 
funeral arrangements were incomplete monday 
