around airfields and several key sites along the coast of saudi 
arabia 
in interviews with reporters who visited the independence as 
members of a pentagon news media pool the pilots said they have 
yet to encounter any iraqi aircraft and are never closer than 200 
miles to iraq 
that leaves them well out of range of iraqs formidable arsenal 
of antiaircraft guns and missiles 
standard military references say iraqi president saddam 
husseins forces have more than 300 surfacetoair missile 
launchers of at least eight different types most are 
sovietdesigned 
some date back to the 1960s when north vietnam shot down scores 
of american raiders with missiles like the radarguided sam6 
which has an 11mile ceiling 
iraq also has the sam9 sam13 and sam14 all of them medium 
or short range two miles to six miles they are designed to 
pursue the infrared signature of a speeding jet iraq also has 
the roland a frenchdesigned sam 
some of the missiles were used in the war with iran but with 
limited effect as tehrans force of usbuilt warplanes was 
depleted by age and a shortage of spare parts 
in the interviews independence combat pilots said they 
respected their iraqi counterparts for their war experience but 
doubted they would challenge the superior american aircraft and 
training 
i have a hard time thinking theyd want to do that they have 
a lot of experience and not many of us have been in combat but 
were not iran either said one pilot of an f18 hornet 
fighterbomber 
said another 29yearold hornet pilot i do feel that our 
biggest threat to losing aircraft to the iraqis is from their sam 
platforms as opposed to their airtoair fighters he said 
a senior commander who like the others could not be identified 
by name under the terms of the interviews said there were 
relatively few dogfight encounters in the gulf war and those 
that did occur were probably chance encounters where neither guy 
got more than one shot 
he said the speed and armament of the f14 tomcats flying the 
patrol missions gave them a clear edge over iraqs frenchbuilt f1 
mirage fighters 
although some sailors grumbled about the tension of waiting for 
something to happen the carriers crew of some 5000 seemed 
generally in high spirits 
capt robert l ellis jr commander of the independence said 
his crew most of whom are 18 to 22 years old werent thinking 
about combat when they embarked on their current tour of duty at 
san diego on june 23 
but now they have a sense of pride that their country has 
responded and they are the ones on the front line ellis said 
in addition to the fighters on patrol missions other aircraft 
thunder constantly off the carriers steam catapults on aerial 
refueling sorties and night landing practices 
small groups of pilots observe and evaluate their colleages as 
the gray jets roar in at maximum power against the wind to catch a 
tailhook on one of the four arresting tables stretched across the 
deck 
most make it the first time but occassionally one overshoots 
the cables and screams off again hook scrapping the bare deck in a 
great shower of sparks 
