<TEXT>
postmaster general anthony m frank 
responding to complaints from senior citizen advocates defended 
his agencys policy of refusing to automatically forward nursing 
home residents mail when they move 
but frank said in a letter to sen john heinz rpa released 
monday that he was disturbed by reports that welltraveled nursing 
home residents mail was being left behind 
i understand you are aware of places where improper mail 
forwarding has caused a hardship for nursing home residents i am 
very concerned with such reports and can assure you the postal 
service is committed to resolving any problems which may exist 
frank said 
the postal service and the senate special committee on aging 
have agreed to collaborate on a campaign to ensure that nursing 
homes are readdressing the mail of residents who have left the 
committee said also frank said the agency has formed an internal 
committee to determine if policy changes are needed 
because all residents of a nursing home are at the same address 
the postal service says the home should be the agent for their 
mail the mail is delivered in bulk like at prisons hotels and 
summer camps and distributed by the institution 
while other people may submit changeofaddress cards to local 
post offices nursing home residents must rely on the institution 
to write their new address on individual letters then the post 
office delivers it at no extra charge 
heinz the aging committees ranking republican questioned the 
policy in a march letter to frank and a florida elderlyrights 
advocate told congress that some mail was not being forwarded and 
the policy treats nursing home residents like they were in jail 
or something 
but frank defended the policy as costeffective and 
practical 
single point delivery permits management of the nursing home 
with specific knowledge of each residents needs and condition to 
properly handle their mail and complete delivery at the best time 
and in the most appropriate manner frank said 
allowing residents to file address forwarding cards would mean 
postal employees sorting mail would need a record of each person in 
the home frank said he said that is not practical because of high 
resident turnover 
also some incapacitated residents might have problems obtaining 
and completing a changeofaddress card frank said 
heinz was reviewing franks letter said aide isabelle claxton 
in the meantime claxton said the postal service has agreed to 
cooperate with the senate panel in writing to more than 10000 
nursing homes certified by the federal government under medicare 
and medicaid the letters will explain to homes their obligation to 
ensure that mail is forwarded 
