<TEXT>
a 4yearold boy got a transfusion of umbilical 
cord blood from his newborn sister monday in an attempt to cure a 
rare and deadly form of leukemia 
it was the first time such a transfusion had been attempted in 
the past bone marrow transplant has been the only treatment to 
increase survival for patients of leukeumia a cancer of the white 
blood cells 
if the transfusion works doctors said it could lead to the 
creation of a bank of such blood that could be transfused into 
children who might die before a sibling donor would be old enough 
to donate bone marrow 
the patient michael sancilio of virginia beach va was 
diagnosed in april as suffering from juvenile chronic myelogenous 
leukemia it cannot be controlled by drugs and usually kills within 
one year of diagnosis 
when michaels sister christina was born may 1 doctors 
collected blood from the cord hoping she would be a suitable donor 
they couldnt wait to use her bone marrow because such a 
transplant cant be performed on children under sixmonths old and 
doctors feared michael could die by then 
the odds were we thought he had the chance of surviving for a 
couple of months but it was unknown when the disease would 
accelerate and become lifethreatening said dr john wagner of 
the johns hopkins oncology center we decided to go ahead and 
take the chance on the cordblood rather than waiting till the 
donor was old enough 
michaels parents and his brother tony 7 werent compatible 
donors 
wagner injected three syringes of cord blood into a vessel near 
michaels heart as the boy dozed in his bed monday wagner said 
the boy had undergone eight days of chemotherapy to destroy his 
cancerous marrow the transfused cells from christina are expected 
to enter his bones and begin forming cancerfree bone marrow in 30 
days wagner said 
cord blood transplants have been performed successfully twice in 
france and once in cincinnati to treat a different disease 
fanconis anemia hopkins doctors said 
blood in the umbilical cord provides nourishment and oxygen to a 
fetus while being carried inside the mother and so differs from 
the babys or the mothers blood 
dr richard champlin chief of the bone marrow transplant 
program at md anderson cancer center in houston said the 
transplant could have longterm significance 
in the long run it could provide the potential to protect and 
store umbilical blood from every baby and create a bank of cells 
for transplantation that could be used if a patient didnt have a 
donor within the family he said 
we hope it may be able to increase the number of donors 
available for patients but it has to pass this test first 
wagner said 
the transplant carries the same risk as a bonemarrow 
transplant the recipients immunity from infection is lowered 
during the procedure and the body often rejects foreign cells 
umbilical cordblood is particularly rich in stem cells which 
the transplant recipients body uses to form marrow but the blood 
could only be transplanted to young children because it doesnt 
contain enough stem cells to build marrow in the bodies of 
adolescents or adults champlin said 
the transplant also raises ethical questions said dr jeff 
malatack a pediatrician at childrens hospital in pittsburgh 
in suburban los angeles parents conceived a baby last year to 
serve as a donor for their cancerstricken daughter anissa ayala 
18 was expected to receive a bonemarrow transplant from her baby 
sister marissa in late summer or in the fall 
is the parent in the right position to offer the procedure be 
done on a 6monthold to save a 4yearold the question will come 
up within families what if it comes up with an unrelated baby 
said malatack 
malatack posited for example that if parents found umbilical 
cord blood in a bank from a baby they thought had similar tissue to 
their sick child they might try to approach that childs parents 
about a possible bone marrow transplant 
someone could say id like to use your baby to put to sleep 
and do a bone marrow harvest so a baby in some other area of the 
country could benefit he said 
