twentynine historically black colleges and 
universities agreed aug 10 to form an association of journalism 
and mass communication programs 
orlando j taylor dean of the school of communications at 
howard university in washington said the group will be called the 
association of black college journalism and mass communication 
programs 
the new organization represents a historic effort to ensure 
that the voices of black colleges and universities will be heard in 
journalism and mass communication education and in the media 
professions he said 
the association is designed to help journalism programs gain 
accreditation and increase the hiring of black journalists and 
other media professionals 
this association wants to destroy the myth that there are no 
qualified black media professionals taylor said 
taylor chairman of the new groups planning committee said 
large us corporations and major foundations will be asked for 
donations 
taylor said the organization plans an intensive study of the 
nature scope and status of all journalism and mass communication 
programs at the nations 117 historically black colleges to be 
accomplished in the coming year in order to provide the data base 
for enhancing these programs 
the new organization was formed during the convention of the 
association for education in journalism and mass communication 
other members of the groups planning committee are elayne 
hayesanthony of jackson state university harry amana of 
clarkatlanta university dianne cherry of hampton university and 
