<TEXT>
when robbie matthew leans back in a 
city armchair and talks about life out on his trapline in northern 
quebec his eyes glisten a soft smile spreads across his face 
come september hell be back out there with his family living in 
a muhtukan hunting and trapping 
city for matthew is chisasibi a cree indian village of 2500 on 
the shore of james bay a thumb of water shooting southeast off 
hudson bay he comes in from the forest for a few weeks at 
christmas then again when the ice breaks 
there im happy he says of the 100mileby40mile 
trapline he runs east of what is now known as the lg2 reservoir 
i enjoy the scenery most of all every year we go out even if 
fur prices are low what would i do here play bingo and watch 
hockey on tv myself i like to move about 
matthew calls himself an old man though he is 56 and he is a 
lucky man the massive 62 billion james bay hydroelectric 
development project did not destroy his trapline as it did some 
others when it covered the land with thousands of square 
kilometers of water 
though his trapline is not submerged he has seen the effects of 
building massive dams and dikes on the magnificent la grande river 
and the construction of hundreds of miles of roads and electric 
transmission lines 
hydro quebec the power company owned by the province of quebec 
says its environmental studies show very little permanent impact on 
the wildlife from 15 years of construction officials say there is 
just as much beaver lynx marten muskrat caribou bear and fish 
as before 
but many of the small creeks are now filled up on matthews trap 
and he says he never sees muskrat any more 
each fall matthew his wife three of his six sons and their 
families head for the trap they construct a winter home of split 
logs placed upright and swamp moss the same stuff we used to 
make baby diapers with from there in cold as much as 45 below 
zero matthew and his family hunt and trap taking just enough to 
eat and to keep the women busy preparing the furs to sell 
and you come back inside where it is so warm he says 
closing his eyes and almost smelling the fire i love that no 
matter how cold it is outside it is always warm inside there all 
winter with your children and grandchildren 
matthew is what is known as a tallyman he is responsible for 
managing the trapline inherited from his uncle that involves 
doing a yearly inventory of the beaver lodges and other animals on 
his trap 
a trapline is like a garden you have to manage it wisely 
he says that includes working some parts of it and letting other 
parts rest for two or three years but not more untrapped 
territory becomes as unproductive as overtrapped territory 
the animals also have their say 
sometimes the animals dont want to be trapped crees say so a 
trapper moves to another area there must be respect for the 
animals or the animals will respond by not letting themselves be 
caught 
matthew is worried about the caribou like all game they are 
cyclical caribou are now abundant but says matthew they are 
acting strangely 
now they are starting to decrease because of all the forest 
fires the wolves are starting to increase and he is finding 
dead caribou in the lakes with no sign of wounds or attack by 
animals 
there is something strange happening with the caribou in the 
old days if he smelled smoke or heard a shot he would run for 
miles now they are not scared anymore you can practically walk 
up and shoot them 
it used to be we really had to hunt and you really had to 
hide yourself and be careful to kill a caribou thats one thing i 
would like these biologists to do is there something wrong with 
the caribou 
he notices other things too 
i think some of that acid rain stuff must be getting here i 
had the strange feeling that trees are a slightly different color 
than usual in spring 
