editors note the key to the church of the holy sepulcher the 
shrine where christ was buried is held by moslems to prevent 
squabbles among christians however it recently has become a 
source of contention between two moslem families in jerusalem 
its joudeh vs nusseibeh 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
abdul khader joudeh held in his outstretched 
hands the rusty 10inch iron key that opens the door to the 
holiest site in christendom the church of the holy sepulcher 
this key is from the time of saladin said joudeh a moslem 
whose family has charge of the key as a way of preventing squabbles 
among rival christian sects over rights to the holy shrine 
now however the key to the shrine where christ was buried has 
set off a jealous conflict between two of jerusalems oldest moslem 
families the joudehs and nusseibehs 
more precisely the vaunted title keeper of the key is at 
issue 
like most such arab disputes this one involves tradition 
family pride and a history that may stretch back to the moslem 
conqueror saladin or even beyond 
when you are the owner of the key for 800 years no one can 
take this right from you said jawad joudeh a brother of abdul 
khader at 65 jawad is the family elder and official key custodian 
wajeeh nusseibeh of the rival clan while he grants the joudehs 
hold the key insists the nusseibehs long link to the holy 
sepulcher gives them the right to the key custodians title too 
when the caliph came to the city of jerusalem the key was 
given to a member of our family says nusseibeh referring to the 
caliph omar the first moslem conqueror of jerusalem in ad 636 
the joudehs dispute that claim and trace their own hold on the 
key to saladin who recaptured jerusalem from the christian 
crusaders in 1187 
both omar and saladin ensured christian rights to the holy 
sepulcher under moslem rule leading to todays traditions of the 
key keeper and the moslem guards in fezzes who still escort bishops 
to the shrine for ceremonies 
the current squabble began last spring when the holy sepulcher 
was closed to protest an effort by jewish settlers to take over a 
building in jerusalems christian quarter news reports at the time 
referred to nusseibeh as keeper of the key 
the joudehs were mortified 
i heard it on radio amman then on radio cairo said abdul 
khader i felt we had been deprived of our rights 
the family put statements of protest in two of jerusalems 
arabic newspapers jawad wrote letters to reporters and abdul 
khader came with documents to news agency offices 
when the family was invited to tell its story the joudeh 
delegation consisted of the two brothers a cousin a friend and 
abdul khaders 24yearold son ahab a graduate student at george 
washington university in washington dc 
the joudehs brought firmans or decrees from the ottoman 
turkish sultans who ruled palestine for 400 years to show the 
familys long possession of the key 
the familys argument explained over cups of thick arabic 
coffee is that the nusseibehs are the door keepers of the 
church not the key keepers 
the joudehs turn the key over to the nusseibehs who then must 
climb a ladder to reach the keyhole insert the key and finally do 
the physical labor of pushing open the heavy wooden door 
this tradition came about abdul khader explained because of 
the stature of his family 
they were all sheiks he said how could they open the 
church how could they push the door everyone was coming to kiss 
their hands so the nusseibeh family was assigned as doorkeepers 
abdul khader added that the nusseibehs gained some note over the 
years including in its numbers government ministers during 
jordanian rule 
they dont want to say they are doorkeepers but that is what 
they are he added 
the joudehs and the nusseibehs agree on one thing the origin of 
the key being put in moslem hands was not to stop fights among 
christians though it evolved into that 
the first reason was saladins fear that crusaders would try to 
regain the church later money got involved when taxes were levied 
on christian pilgrims with proceeds going to moslem charities and 
the families controlling the door 
at the time of the ottoman empirewe were receiving a good 
income said abdul khader 
the practice of taxing pilgrims ended in the 1800s however 
wajeeh nusseibeh says that together the two families now get about 
20 a month from the greek orthodox roman catholic and armenian 
churches 
it doesnt cover transportation or breakfast or dinner for 
even one day he added we do the job out of pride 
in fact both families pay workers actually to open the church 
at 430 am each day and close it in the evening the joudehs and 
nusseibehs only open the doors on special occasions like easter 
wajeeh nusseibeh 39 took over his church duties when his 
father died in 1982 he maintained that his family was not only 
given the key to the church by caliph omar but again by saladin 
after he drove the crusaders from jerusalem 
saladin asked for the key from the nusseibehs and he gave it 
back he said 
he added that the joudehs got involved in the process later 
nusseibeh said he accepts the joudehs job descriptions that 
they hold the key and he opens the door i believe its important 
who opens the door he added 
what bothers him is the suggestion that his family has no 
association with the key that the nusseibehs are somehow late 
arrivals in the arab history of jerusalem 
we came before the joudehs he said we are the most 
ancient family in jerusalem 
and in this battle of firmans and families who is right 
it turns out both joudehs and nusseibehs are partly right 
according to the status quo the rules on rights to jerusalems 
holy sites that were formulated by the turks cataloged under 
british rule of palestine and still used by israel 
the idea was to keep the christians from fighting among 
themselves and the turks were precise their rules say which 
candle in the holy sepulcher each christian sect may light which 
scrap of floor it must sweep 
as for the church door the status quo states the tradition 
of moslem guardians dates from the time of caliph omar but it 
makes no mention of saladins awarding of the key 
it says though that when moslems fully dislodged the crusaders 
from jerusalem in 1289 the custody of the keys was given to the 
family of el insaibi nusseibeh to prevent disputes between the 
various christian communities 
later the document says the guardianship was divided with the 
judeh family it adds 
this is the position at the present time the judeh family 
holding the keys and the insaibi having charge of the actual 
opening of the door 
</TEXT>
