<DOCNO> AP900813-0179 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
 
editors note rougham airfield may go the way of its planes 
and fliers into history but for the moment there are still 
reminders of what some american servicemen accomplished nearly 50 
years ago during the dark days of world war ii 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
silence and fog hung over what 
was left of a runway at rougham airfield where american fliers had 
roared off to raid german targets during world war ii 
the peacefulness contrasted with my grandfathers memories of 
the us 8th air force base the rumble of scores of engines in the 
air dogfights overhead a b17 landing with heavy battle damage 
every man aboard wounded every cartridge aboard fired the 
aircraft itself dripping blood 
cpl t morgan daniel had served as a mechanic here with the 
94th bomb group 331st squadron during world war ii 
he doubted anything remained of this airfield but on a side 
trip during a vacation i found remnants of runways huts used for 
storage and housing a control tower and a community that still 
identifies itself by what americans did here almost 50 years ago 
rougham is in the east anglia region of england flat farm 
country juting into the north sea its location and terrain 
tailormade for air bases designed to hit germany and occupied 
europe 
inside the flying fortress pub on the base site the walls are 
lined with photographs of men in leather jackers crouched in neat 
rows before planes painted with what was called nose art cartoons 
illustrated the planes nicknames eighth air force bombers sported 
names such as royal flush southern comfort the eagles 
wrath and rain of terror 
a wooden plaque in the pub carries the a that adorned the 
tails of the bombers that flew from here and says 94th bomb 
group 19421945 
the pub also features a print showing b17s in flight the 
painting looked familiar i had seen it before in my grandfathers 
house the handiwork of a comrade in arms 
an american accent and a mention of the 8th air force brings a 
warm welcome in bury st edmunds and at the flying fortress 
there is an awful lot of good feeling toward the americans who 
were here during the war said keith allchin the pubs owner 
the feeling is mutual my grandfather used to talk fondly about 
the hospitality of the english and dinners at their homes 
allchin said up to 400 american veterans have visited since the 
flying fortress opened in december 1988 
theyre pleased to think theyre remembered he said they 
seem to think a lot of people have forgotten all about them 
veterans and those visiting on behalf of veterans are asked to 
sign a guest book kept at the bar a bartender also gave me a map 
of rougham as it was during wartime to help identify what remains 
finding those remnants isnt easy rougham airfield originally 
a british royal air force base was camouflaged in its time 
the luftwaffe bombed all around us but they never found us 
my grandfather used to say 
and for all practical purposes rougham is still camouflaged 
a narrow twisting road leads from bury st edmunds to the 
airfield site or the aerodrome as the british call it other than 
the pubs sign nothing visible on mount road indicates that part 
of the air power that liberated europe was launched from here 
an official military account of the 8th air forces first year 
over europe quotes virgil germany heard a clashing of arms all 
over the sky the alps trembled with uncommon earthquakes never 
did lightnings fall in greater quantities from a serene sky or 
dire thunders blaze so often 
local residents confirmed that part of rougham airfield still 
existed and provided directions 
amid fields of wheat barley and sugar beets one finds part of 
the runways cracked and broken in a heavy mist they appear to 
recede into the past and a walk down one of them seems to go on 
forever instead of warplanes tractors now roll down the runways 
farmers use some of the airmens huts as storage sheds 
in a heavy british fog the kind that might have grounded a 
bombing mission the huts materialize like ghosts as one approaches 
a bumpy muddy path leads to what had been the control tower 
locals say an elderly woman made the tower her home until her death 
about 18 months ago the tower is now hidden among trees and high 
weeds 
rougham industrial estate a small industrial park has grown up 
around other buildings 
and some of those structures have found a modern use according 
to allchin 
a hanger itself is a seed storage depot allchin said he 
also said an environmental group is refurbishing the old chapel and 
gym to turn it into a village hall 
eventually rougham airfield may go the way of its planes and 
fliers into history allchin said a developer is seeking 
permission to build housing on the site 
the lightning and thunder launched against targets such as 
german aircraft factories and submarine pens have long since 
stilled but at least for now one can find a few silent reminders 
</TEXT>
