<TEXT>
by the turn of the century american farmers 
are going to gain at least 34 million acres of cropland a 
potential surge in production capacity that already has some people 
concerned 
the additional cropland is currently tied up in the 
governments conservation reserve program under 10year contracts 
that will begin to expire in 1996 the last of the crp land will be 
freed up in 1999 
some refinements of the crp are included in 1990 farm bills 
passed by the house and senate including amendments to extend the 
enrollment period through the 1995 crop year those details will be 
worked out in conference negotiations in the coming weeks 
but the basic program authorized in the 1985 farm law remains 
pretty much the same as set up by the agriculture department 
signups began in 1986 and the last were held a year ago 
even without the uncertainties caused by federal budgetary 
pressures and the pressures on congress to tinker with the program 
its tough to make predictions about the future of crp and its 
impact on agricultural production 
a recent report by the general accounting office the 
investigative arm of congress cited a number of factors that 
relate to the future of us crop production and therefore the 
crp 
natural conditions which could limit the available land for 
agricultural use and could influence the quality or quantity of 
production national conditions include location climate soil 
conditions and proximity to water 
economic conditions including the price and availability of 
labor and capital also it would include domestic and 
international patterns of production and consumption and exports 
and imports 
public policies including federal state and local efforts 
that directly or indirectly influence agricultural production 
local zoning regulation for the control of pesticides could 
influence yields for example 
the gao report looking at the possibilities for steppedup 
production once the longterm crp contracts have expired said much 
will depend on decisions of individual farmers on whether to 
continue idling their land or returning it to productive use 
for example about 6 percent of the crp acreage has been 
planted with trees the report said assumptions about the 
extent to which these 2 million acres of trees will be cleared and 
returned to cropland would be a consideration in determining the 
crps impact on production 
the crp is expected to cost the government about 146 billion 
over the life of its contracts 
about 13 billion comes from the annual rental payments received 
by farmers for idling and protecting their land those payments 
average about 49 per acre per year farmers also get initial 
costsharing for planting grass or trees to protect the soil 
thus the crp makes a significant contribution to farm income 
and producers faced with the end of payments will be making 
decisions on what to do next 
because farmers will not be obligated to maintain the crp 
conservation covers grass and trees after contracts expire most 
crp land is likely to revert to crop production if prices and 
commodity programs are favorable says an agriculture department 
analysis 
this will not be a wholesale acreforacre switch back to crop 
production compliance provisions of other parts of federal law 
relating to conservation will continue to be factors and lawmakers 
in the next several years may make further modifications 
meanwhile the analysis by the departments economic research 
service shows that the crp is helping boost market prices and farm 
income by reducing crop production from levels that otherwise would 
be attained 
overall that may amount to 21 billion to 63 billion over 
the life of the crp the report said this would be in addition to 
the 13 billion in total annual rental payments 
after 1995 when land initially enrolled in the crp may come 
back into production net farm income will begin to slide as crop 
prices drift down the report said 
on the consumer side the report said retail food costs are 
increasing less than 1 percent in any year because of the land 
idled under crp 
but in total the present value of crprelated increases in 
consumer costs is estimated to be 29 billion to 78 billion over 
the programs life the report said 
</TEXT>
