<TEXT>
the united states should be prepared to tap its 
strategic crude oil reserve in case the boycott of iraqi and 
kuwaiti oil creates an insurmountable shortage the head of an 
industry group said today 
president bush should give very serious consideration to 
releasing that oil said charles j dibona president of the 
american petroleum institute there is no immediate pressure to 
do that but that could change and we should be prepared to do 
that 
the white house said late last week that it had no plans to open 
the nations strategic petroleum reserve a vast quantity of crude 
stockpiled in response to the arab embargo oil shocks of the 1970s 
the reserve is stored in underground salt caverns in louisiana 
and is said to contain several hundred days worth of emergency 
supplies 
oil prices climbed again this morning because of the uncertainty 
in the middle east the price of west texas intermediate the 
benchmark us crude rose 47 cents a barrel to 2670 by late 
morning on the new york mercantile exchange oil fetched 21 a 
barrel just before iraq seized kuwait aug 2 
it might take a few weeks for the government to gear up to 
auction the oil held in the strategic petroleum reserve so 
preparations for opening the reserve should be made now to avoid 
any delays dibona said the turmoil in the world oil markets 
caused by iraqs invasion of kuwait is clearly the kind of 
circumstance for which the oil reserve was designed dibona said 
he told a news conference that the immediate fate of the oil 
supply will hinge on the willingness of foreign producers to make 
up nearly 4 million barrels per day that had been exported by iraq 
and kuwait 
saudi arabia a key gulf producer has indicated a willingness 
to help dibona said so has venezuela and to the extent they 
do they will largely make up the 4 million barrel per day 
shortfall however no one can know at this point what the net 
effect on world oil supplies will be 
dibona said there are other steps the united states can take to 
lessen the effects of the higher prices 
he called on the government to open the point arguello oilfield 
off the coast of california which he said is sitting idle because 
california officials have not given oil companies permission to 
deliver their oil the field could immediately produce 90000 
barrels per day dibona said 
consumers could ease the crisis by conserving the oil they use 
and by resisting the temptation to top off their tanks or hoard 
supplies although conservation will not be enough to solve the 
problem dibona said 
asked about complaints from consumers that oil companies have 
been unfairly raising prices dibona reiterated the industrys view 
that the companies have shown restraint retail prices of gasoline 
have not risen nearly as high as spot market prices or wholesale 
prices he said 
the petroleum industry has not taken advantage of this 
international crisis in a selfserving way dibona said dibona 
declined to predict what will happen to prices in the future 
increased domestic production could also alleviate the oil 
crisis dibona said but oil companies base their plans for more 
exploration on their projections of prices over a long term the 
prices have been changing too rapidly in recent days to permit any 
such longterm planning dibona said 
