<DOCNO> AP900813-0211 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
much of the immediate reactions in securities 
markets after the iraqi invasion of kuwait was based on fears of an 
oil shortage and a runup in the price of fuel as in 1973 and 1979 
but much has changed since then a good deal of it though not 
all for the better 
some of the conservation program has been junked for example 
but it has left a legacy of better insulated houses more efficient 
combustion engines and less reliance on oil and parts of the 
program can be resurrected 
the political situation has changed 
back then the organization of petroleum exporting nations was 
united in efforts to raise prices and the world powers were still 
antagonistic toward each others plans whatever they were 
today much of the arab world opposes iraqs actions and the 
worlds powers seem more accommodating to each others hopes for 
the future opec seems willing to allow production to rise 
stability is another widely shared goal 
oil reserves of the western world and japan today are massively 
higher than before the united states has close to a billion 
barrels in strategic and commercial oil stocks relative to usage 
japan may have more 
meanwhile the lesson of the 1970s was not entirely wasted 
philadelphia electric now relies heavily on nuclear power 
generating less than 5 percent of its electricty from oil new 
england electric has cut its reliance in half 
the economic situation has changed 
in the 1970s the us economy was effectively out of control 
with prices and interest rates high or rising as a result the 
federal reserve tightened its monetary policy hoping to slow the 
economy 
in 1990 the economy has many weak spots debt for instance 
that pose more critical dangers than a temporary increase in the 
price of oil the economy as a whole is under a tightfisted 
monetary policy 
moreover when the fed pushed up shortterm interest rates in 
the earlier crises it precipitated recessions the second one 
considered to be among the worst of the century it isnt likely to 
commit that error again 
while a prolonged shortage of oil or extreme prices could be 
debilitating to the american economy that prospect is not nearly 
so high today as it was in the 1970s when major oil producing 
countries were united in their stand 
a shortterm cut in the flow of oil from abroad still would 
affect prices but perhaps to a smaller degree than many people 
fear in the absence of panic says economist roger brinner a 
2abarrel rise seems likely in 1991 
by his calculations for drimcgrawhill an important provider 
of economic data to the private sector this would imply a 5 
percent gain in the average wholesale price of all fuel and power 
while that 2abarrel increase would be close to 10 percent he 
reasons that the significant roles of nuclear hydro and coal 
generation would dilute the effect on delivered prices 
the consumer impact would be even less he says because 
household spending on energy is 55 percent of all consumer 
purchases the direct inflation impact is about a quarter of a 
percentage point 5 percent of 55 percent 
the spillover from other product and labor markets could add to 
this impact brinner believes it might mean a total price bulge of 
05 percent but not to any material sustained increase in the 
rate of inflation 
a more optimistic scenario than many would paint of course and 
it never should be forgotten that economic projections have a 
tendency to be revised when confronted with reality 
</TEXT>
