<TEXT>
a wall street blackout displaced iraqs saddam 
hussein as the bogeyman of the us financial markets monday 
disrupting trading in stocks bonds currencies and commodites 
the fire at a con edison power substation forced the american 
stock exchange new york mercantile exchange and other futures 
markets in southern manhattan to close by early afternoon 
the new york stock exchange was unaffected by the outage but 
trading volume slowed at the nations biggest stock market as 
electricitystarved offices elsewhere in the financial district 
emptied 
thousands of workers from secretaries to investment bankers 
flooded into trafficsnarled streets and headed home early 
yellowtinged smoke from the substation fire billowed through the 
skyscraper canyons of southern manhattan amid the confusion oil 
prices rose gold surged stocks and bonds were mixed and the 
dollar fell 
amex spokesman robert shabazian said power was restored by late 
afternoon and it planned to reopen tuesday morning as normal he 
also said were making provisions for auxiliary power in the 
event theres another outage 
the disruptions in trading caused by the fire added to the 
pressure bearing down on the markets since iraqs invasion of 
kuwait aug 2 among the markets that were forced to close early 
was the volatile oil futures market at the new york merc 
it greatly affected us said peter stern a dealer at refco 
inc a leading new york commodities futures concern our phones 
went down our screens went down a lot of people went home 
the fire forced an evacuation of several buildings including 
parts of the world trade center and world financial center 
complexes that frame southern manhattans skyline leaving some of 
the nations biggest brokerage operations functioning with skeletal 
crews 
it briefly stalled the dow jones news service and caused a more 
serious and prolonged disruption to the telerate inc news service 
two of the principal information pipelines feeding the markets 
in addition the fire hampered trading far beyond new yorks 
borders since many key dealers based in the affected area were 
forced to curtail business this meant they could not move price 
information to the network of computer screens and telephones that 
form part of a global trading system 
to sum it up real simple the bond market more or less shut 
