<TEXT>
union lawyers filed an unfair 
labor practices complaint with the national labor relations board 
monday over western union corps lockout of about 2000 workers 
at the same time employees represented by the communications 
workers of america have set up informational picket lines at 
western union telephone and computer centers but said they had no 
plans to call a strike 
in its brief to the washingtonbased labor board the cwa 
accused western union of acting illegally by imposing a selective 
lockout on saturday 
about 500 service and business representatives administrative 
clerks and technicians have been asked to continue work said 
george kohl the unions director of research 
lawyers also are protesting that some temporary workers earn 
more than union employees and that the company violated the 
workers rights to bargain and strike by locking them out 
kohl said he expects the labor relations board to set a calendar 
date tuesday 
union employees have been hoisting signs and distributing 
information since the lockout was declared saturday but the 
unions chief negotiator dan j beckstead said the cwa has no 
plans to call a strike 
it is not a strike beckstead said taking pains to 
distinguish between the informational picket lines and strike 
lines no one has even suggested that we are going to strike 
union employees authorized a walkout two weeks ago but set no 
date for a strike said beckstead president of the communications 
workers of americaunited telegraph workers bargaining council 
monday both sides expressed a desire to continue the contract 
negotiations that began july 23 two weeks before a twoyear 
contract was due to expire 
talks continued after the agreement expired aug 6 but ran 
aground on the companys desire to pare down medical benefits and 
to contract union work to outside firms beckstead said 
western union served notice saturday that it would replace most 
of its union employees unless labor officials reconsidered the 
companys aug 8 offer to extend the expired contract by 90 days 
some temporary workers were on the job by 1 am saturday with 
2200 replacements reporting to work monday morning said western 
union spokesman warren bechtel 
about 300 of the workers are western union managers and the rest 
are locally hired and trained replacements he said 
union workers total nearly 75 percent of the companys 
nationwide staff of 3400 bechtel said 
operations at the giant telegram company have been slowed but 
not disrupted bechtel said 
services are being provided and the level of service is good 
and getting better he said you dont replace trained 
experienced people and overnight come up to same level of service 
but were working on it 
monday pickets were concentrated at western union centers in 
bridgeton mo and reno nev where major central phone bureaus 
and a computer center are located beckstead said 
